    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-10-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-10-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="40"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d40">
                <head>40. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_KRW2" type="from">Robert W.
                        Komer</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d40fn1">Source:
                        Johnson Library, National Security File, Name File, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KRW2">Komer</persName> Memos, Vol. II. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-10-15">October 15, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Mac</persName>—</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>, on <hi rend="italic">Indian Ocean
                        bases</hi> I find that all seems to be under control. <persName
                        corresp="#p_KJC1">Kitchen</persName> in London a few weeks ago managed to
                    settle matters with the <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>. They have since told
                    Mauritius it could have its independence but that the Chagos Archipelago (Diego
                    Garcia) would be detached.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KJC1">Kitchen</persName> suspects that the Brits may have
                    over-read a new development—we now wonder whether a commo relay station in Diego
                    Garcia would be as useful as a communications satellite. This is simply
                    technological progress, not a loss of interest. At any rate, the Navy is simply
                    holding up budgeting till this matter is sorted out.</p>
                <p>You probably know better than I that the Brits are probing for US subsidies on
                    various specifics East of Suez. I gather our position is that these matters can
                    only be discussed as part of a much larger issue, including our support of
                    sterling.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KRW2">
                            <hi rend="strong">RWK</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
